\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]But what went all of you out in order to see? A prophet? Yea, I say unto you, and much more than a prophet.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]This is he, of whom it is written, Behold, I send my messenger before your face, which shall prepare your way before you.
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]For I say unto you, Among those that are born of women there is not a greater prophet than John the Baptist: but he that is least in the kingdom of God is greater than he.
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]And all the people that heard him, and the publicans, justified God, being baptized with the baptism of John.
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]But the Pharisees and lawyers rejected the counsel of God against themselves, being not baptized of him.
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]And the Lord said, Unto which then shall I liken the men of this generation? and to what are they like?
\*[SUP]32\*[SUPX]They are like unto children sitting in the marketplace, and calling one to another, and saying, We have piped unto you, and all of you have not danced; we have mourned to you, and all of you have not wept.
\*[SUP]33\*[SUPX]For John the Baptist came neither eating bread nor drinking wine; and all of you say, He has a devil.
\*[SUP]34\*[SUPX]The Son of man has come eating and drinking; and all of you say, Behold a gluttonous man, and a wine indulger, a friend of publicans and sinners!
\*[SUP]35\*[SUPX]But wisdom is justified of all her children.
\*[SUP]36\*[SUPX]And one of the Pharisees desired him that he would eat with him. And he went into the Pharisee's house, and sat down to food.
\*[SUP]37\*[SUPX]And, behold, a woman in the city, which was a sinner, when she knew that Jesus sat at food in the Pharisee's house, brought an alabaster box of ointment,
\*[SUP]38\*[SUPX]And stood at his feet behind him weeping, and began to wash his feet with tears, and did wipe them with the hairs of her head, and kissed his feet, and anointed them with the ointment.
\*[SUP]39\*[SUPX]Now when the Pharisee which had bidden him saw it, he spoke within himself, saying, This man, if he were a prophet, would have known who and what manner of woman this is that touches him: for she is a sinner.
\*[SUP]40\*[SUPX]And Jesus answering said unto him, Simon, I have somewhat to say unto you. And he says, Master, say on.
\*[SUP]41\*[SUPX]There was a certain creditor which had two debtors: the one owed five hundred pence, and the other fifty.
\*[SUP]42\*[SUPX]And when they had nothing to pay, he frankly forgave them both. Tell me therefore, which of them will love him most?
\*[SUP]43\*[SUPX]Simon answered and said, I suppose that he, to whom he forgave most. And he said unto him, You have rightly judged.
\*[SUP]44\*[SUPX]And he turned to the woman, and said unto Simon, See you this woman? I entered into yours house, you gave me no water for my feet: but she has washed my feet with tears, and wiped them with the hairs of her head.
\*[SUP]45\*[SUPX]You gave me no kiss: but this woman since the time I came in has not ceased to kiss my feet.
\*[SUP]46\*[SUPX]My head with oil you did not anoint: but this woman has anointed my feet with ointment.
\*[SUP]47\*[SUPX]Wherefore I say unto you, Her sins, which are many, are forgiven; for she loved much: but to whom little is forgiven, the same loves little.
\*[SUP]48\*[SUPX]And he said unto her, Your sins are forgiven.
\*[SUP]49\*[SUPX]And they that sat at food with him began to say within themselves, Who is this that forgives sins also?
\*[SUP]50\*[SUPX]And he said to the woman, Your faith has saved you; go in peace.
