fter these things Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth;
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]And found a certain Jew named Aquila, born in Pontus, lately come from Italy, with his wife Priscilla; (because that Claudius had commanded all Jews to depart from Rome:) and came unto them.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]And because he was of the same craft, he abode with them, and wrought: for by their occupation they were tentmakers.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]And he reasoned in the synagogue every sabbath, and persuaded the Jews and the Greeks.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]And when Silas and Timotheus were come from Macedonia, Paul was pressed in the spirit,  and testified to the Jews that Jesus was Christ.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]And when they opposed themselves, and blasphemed, he shook his raiment, and said unto them, Your blood be upon your own heads; I am clean; from henceforth I will go unto the Gentiles.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]And he departed thence, and entered into a certain man's house, named Justus, one that worshipped God, whose house joined hard to the synagogue.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]And Crispus, the chief ruler of the synagogue, believed on the Lord with all his house; and many of the Corinthians hearing believed, and were baptized.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]Then spoke the Lord to Paul in the night by a vision, Be not afraid, but speak, and hold not your peace:
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]For I am with you, and no man shall set on you to hurt you: for I have much people in this city.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]And he continued there a year and six months, teaching the word  of God among them.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]And when Gallio was the deputy of Achaia, the Jews made insurrection with one accord against Paul, and brought him to the judgment seat,
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Saying, This fellow persuades men to worship God contrary to the law.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]And when Paul was now about to open his mouth, Gallio said unto the Jews, If it were a matter of wrong or wicked lewdness, O all of you Jews, reason  would that I should bear with you:
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]But if it be a question of words  and names, and of your law, look all of you to it; for I will be no judge of such matters.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]And he drove them from the judgment seat.
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]Then all the Greeks took Sosthenes, the chief ruler of the synagogue, and beat him before the judgment seat. And Gallio cared for none of those things.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]And Paul after this tarried there yet a good while, and then took his leave of the brethren, and sailed thence into Syria, and with him Priscilla and Aquila; having shorn his head in Cenchrea: for he had a vow.
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]And he came to Ephesus, and left them there: but he himself entered into the synagogue, and reasoned with the Jews.
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]When they desired him to tarry longer time with them, he consented not;
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]But bade them farewell, saying, I must by all means keep this feast that comes in Jerusalem: but I will return again unto you, if God will. And he sailed from Ephesus.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]And when he had landed at Caesarea, and gone up, and saluted the church, he went down to Antioch.
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]And after he had spent some time there, he departed, and went over all the country of Galatia and Phrygia in order, strengthening all the disciples.
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]And a certain Jew named Apollos, born at Alexandria, an eloquent man, and mighty in the scriptures, came to Ephesus.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]This man was instructed in the way of the Lord; and being fervent in the spirit,  he spoke and taught diligently the things of the Lord, knowing only the baptism of John.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]And he began to speak boldly in the synagogue: whom when Aquila and Priscilla had heard, they took him unto them, and expounded unto him the way of God more perfectly.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]And when he was disposed to pass into Achaia, the brethren wrote, exhorting the disciples to receive him: who, when he was come, helped them much which had believed through grace:
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]For he mightily convinced the Jews, and that publicly, showing by the scriptures that Jesus was Christ.
