nd after the uproar was ceased, Paul called unto him the disciples, and embraced them, and departed in order to go into Macedonia.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]And when he had gone over those parts, and had given them much exhortation,  he came into Greece,
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]And there abode three months. And when the Jews laid wait for him, as he was about to sail into Syria, he purposed to return through Macedonia.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]And there accompanied him into Asia Sopater of Berea; and of the Thessalonians, Aristarchus and Secundus; and Gaius of Derbe, and Timotheus; and of Asia, Tychicus and Trophimus.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]These going before tarried for us at Troas.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]And we sailed away from Philippi after the days of unleavened bread, and came unto them to Troas in five days; where we abode seven days.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]And upon the first day of the week, when the disciples came together to break bread, Paul preached unto them, ready to depart on the next day; and continued his speech  until midnight.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]And there were many lights in the upper chamber, where they were gathered together.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]And there sat in a window a certain young man named Eutychus, being fallen into a deep sleep: and as Paul was long preaching, he sunk down with sleep, and fell down from the third upper room, and was taken up dead.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]And Paul went down, and fell on him, and embracing him said, Trouble not yourselves; for his life is in him.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]When he therefore was come up again, and had broken bread, and eaten, and talked a long while, even till break of day, so he departed.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]And they brought the young man alive, and were not a little comforted.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]And we went on board ship, and sailed unto Assos, there intending to take in Paul: for so had he appointed, minding himself to go on foot.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]And when he met with us at Assos, we took him in, and came to Mitylene.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]And we sailed thence, and came the next day opposite to Chios; and the next day we arrived at Samos, and tarried at Trogyllium; and the next day we came to Miletus.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]For Paul had determined to sail by Ephesus, because he would not spend the time in Asia: for he hasted, if it were possible for him, to be at Jerusalem the day of Pentecost.
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]And from Miletus he sent to Ephesus, and called the elders of the church.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]And when they were come to him, he said unto them, All of you know, from the first day that I came into Asia, after what manner I have been with you at all seasons,
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]Serving the LORD with all humility of mind, and with many tears, and temptations, which befell me by the lying in wait of the Jews:
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]And how I kept back nothing that was profitable unto you, but have showed you, and have taught you publicly, and from house to house,
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]Testifying both to the Jews, and also to the Greeks, repentance toward God, and faith toward our Lord Jesus Christ.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]And now, behold, I go bound in the spirit  unto Jerusalem, not knowing the things that shall befall me there:
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]Save that the Holy Spirit  witnesses in every city, saying that bonds and afflictions abide me.
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]But none of these things  move me, neither count I my life dear unto myself, so that I might finish my course with joy, and the ministry, which I have received of the Lord Jesus, to testify the gospel of the grace of God.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]And now, behold, I know that all of you all, among whom I have gone preaching the kingdom of God, shall see my face no more.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]Wherefore I take you to record this day, that I am pure from the blood of all men.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]For I have not shunned to declare unto you all the counsel of God.
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]Take heed therefore unto yourselves, and to all the flock, over the which the Holy Spirit  has made you overseers, to feed the church of God, which he has purchased with his own blood.
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]For I know this, that after my departing shall grievous wolves enter in among you, not sparing the flock.
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]Also of your own selves shall men arise, speaking perverse things, to draw away disciples after them.
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]Therefore watch, and remember, that by the space of three years I ceased not to warn every one night and day with tears.
\*[SUP]32\*[SUPX]And now, brethren, I commend you to God, and to the word  of his grace, which is able to build you up, and to give you an inheritance among all them which are sanctified.
\*[SUP]33\*[SUPX]I have coveted no man's silver, or gold, or apparel.
\*[SUP]34\*[SUPX]Yea, all of you yourselves know, that these hands have ministered unto my necessities, and to them that were with me.
\*[SUP]35\*[SUPX]I have showed you all things, how that so labouring all of you ought to support the weak, and to remember the words  of the Lord Jesus, how he said, It is more blessed to give than to receive.
\*[SUP]36\*[SUPX]And when he had thus spoken, he kneeled down, and prayed with them all.
\*[SUP]37\*[SUPX]And they all wept sore, and fell on Paul's neck, and kissed him,
\*[SUP]38\*[SUPX]Sorrowing most of all for the words  which he spoke, that they should see his face no more. And they accompanied him unto the ship.
