\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]But now we are delivered from the law, that being dead wherein we were held; that we should serve in newness of spirit,  and not in the oldness of the letter.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]What shall we say then? Is the law sin? God forbid. Nay, I had not known sin, but by the law: for I had not known lust, except the law had said, You shall not covet.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]But sin, taking occasion by the commandment, wrought in me all manner of concupiscence. For without the law sin was dead.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]For I was alive without the law once: but when the commandment came, sin revived, and I died.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]And the commandment, which was ordained to life, I found to be unto death.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]For sin, taking occasion by the commandment, deceived me, and by it slew me.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]Wherefore the law is holy, and the commandment holy, and just, and good.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Was then that which is good made death unto me? God forbid. But sin, that it might appear sin, working death in me by that which is good; that sin by the commandment might become exceeding sinful.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]For we know that the law is spiritual: but I am carnal, sold under sin.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]For that which I do I allow not: for what I would, that do I not; but what I hate, that do I.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]If then I do that which I would not, I consent unto the law that it is good.
