e all of you followers of me, even as I also am of Christ.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]Now I praise you, brethren, that all of you remember me in all things, and keep the ordinances, as I delivered them to you.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]But I would have you know, that the head of every man is Christ; and the head of the woman is the man; and the head of Christ is God.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]Every man praying or prophesying, having his head covered, dishonours his head.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]But every woman that prays or prophesies with her head uncovered dishonours her head: for that is even all one as if she were shaven.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]For if the woman be not covered, let her also be shorn: but if it be a shame for a woman to be shorn or shaven, let her be covered.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]For a man indeed ought not to cover his head, forasmuch as he is the image and glory of God: but the woman is the glory of the man.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]For the man is not of the woman: but the woman of the man.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]Neither was the man created for the woman; but the woman for the man.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]For this cause ought the woman to have power on her head because of the angels.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]Nevertheless neither is the man without the woman, neither the woman without the man, in the Lord.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]For as the woman is of the man, even so is the man also by the woman; but all things of God.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Judge in yourselves: is it comely that a woman pray unto God uncovered?
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]Does not even nature itself teach you, that, if a man have long hair, it is a shame unto him?
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]But if a woman have long hair, it is a glory to her: for her hair is given her for a covering.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]But if any man seem to be contentious, we have no such custom, neither the churches of God.
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]Now in this that I declare unto you I praise you not, that all of you come together not for the better, but for the worse.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]For first of all, when all of you come together in the church, I hear that there be divisions among you; and I partly believe it.
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]For there must be also heresies among you, that they which are approved may be made manifest among you.
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]When all of you come together therefore into one place, this is not to eat the Lord's supper.
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]For in eating every one takes before other his own supper: and one is hungry, and another is drunken.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]What? have all of you not houses to eat and to drink in? or despise all of you the church of God, and shame them that have not? What shall I say to you? shall I praise you in this? I praise you not.
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]For I have received of the Lord that which also I delivered unto you, That the Lord Jesus the same night in which he was betrayed took bread:
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]And when he had given thanks, he brake it, and said, Take, eat: this is my body, which is broken for you: this do in remembrance of me.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]After the same manner also he took the cup, when he had supped, saying, This cup is the new testament in my blood: this do all of you, as often as all of you drink it, in remembrance of me.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]For as often as all of you eat this bread, and drink this cup, all of you do show the Lord's death till he comes.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]Wherefore whosoever shall eat this bread, and drink this cup of the Lord, unworthily, shall be guilty of the body and blood of the Lord.
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]But let a man examine himself, and so let him eat of that bread, and drink of that cup.
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]For he that eats and drinks unworthily, eats and drinks damnation to himself, not discerning the Lord's body.
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]For this cause many are weak and sickly among you, and many sleep.
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]For if we would judge ourselves, we should not be judged.
\*[SUP]32\*[SUPX]But when we are judged, we are chastened of the Lord, that we should not be condemned with the world.
\*[SUP]33\*[SUPX]Wherefore, my brethren, when all of you come together to eat, tarry one for another.
\*[SUP]34\*[SUPX]And if any man hunger, let him eat at home; that all of you come not together unto condemnation. And the rest will I set in order when I come.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 12"
.\"
.PP
.DROPCAP "N" 2 COND 90
ow concerning spiritual gifts, brethren, I would not have you ignorant.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]All of you know that all of you were Gentiles, carried away unto these dumb idols, even as all of you were led.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]Wherefore I give you to understand, that no man speaking by the Spirit  of God calls Jesus accursed: and that no man can say that Jesus is the Lord, but by the Holy Spirit.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]Now there are diversities of gifts, but the same Spirit.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]And there are differences of administrations, but the same Lord.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]And there are diversities of operations, but it is the same God which works all in all.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]But the manifestation of the Spirit  is given to every man to profit likewise.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]In order to one is given by the Spirit  the word  of wisdom; to another the word  of knowledge by the same Spirit;
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]To another faith by the same Spirit;  to another the gifts of healing by the same Spirit;
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]To another the working of miracles; to another prophecy; to another discerning of spirits;  to another divers kinds of tongues; to another the interpretation of tongues:
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]But all these works that one and the very same Spirit,  dividing to every man severally as he will.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]For as the body is one, and has many members, and all the members of that one body, being many, are one body: so also is Christ.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]For by one Spirit  are we all baptized into one body, whether we be Jews or Gentiles, whether we be bond or free; and have been all made to drink into one Spirit.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]For the body is not one member, but many.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]If the foot shall say, Because I am not the hand, I am not of the body; is it therefore not of the body?
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]And if the ear shall say, Because I am not the eye, I am not of the body; is it therefore not of the body?
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]If the whole body were an eye, where were the hearing? If the whole were hearing, where were the smelling?
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]But now has God set the members every one of them in the body, as it has pleased him.
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]And if they were all one member, where were the body?
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]But now are they many members, yet but one body.
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]And the eye cannot say unto the hand, I have no need of you: nor again the head to the feet, I have no need of you.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]Nay, much more those members of the body, which seem to be more feeble, are necessary:
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]And those members of the body, which we think to be less honourable, upon these we bestow more abundant honour; and our indecent parts have more abundant loveliness.
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]For our comely parts have no need: but God has tempered the body together, having given more abundant honour to that part which lacked.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]That there should be no division in the body; but that the members should have the same care one for another.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]And whether one member suffer, all the members suffer with it; or one member be honoured, all the members rejoice with it.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]Now all of you are the body of Christ, and members in particular.
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]And God has set some in the church, first apostles, secondly prophets, thirdly teachers, after that miracles, then gifts of healings, helps, governments, diversities of tongues.
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]Are all apostles? are all prophets? are all teachers? are all workers of miracles?
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]Have all the gifts of healing? do all speak with tongues? do all interpret?
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]But covet earnestly the best gifts: and yet show I unto you a more excellent way.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 13"
.\"
.PP
.DROPCAP "T" 2 COND 90
hough I speak with the tongues of men and of angels, and have not love,  I am become as sounding brass, or a tinkling cymbal.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]And though I have the gift of prophecy, and understand all mysteries, and all knowledge; and though I have all faith, so that I could remove mountains, and have not love,  I am nothing.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]And though I bestow all my goods to feed the poor, and though I give my body to be burned, and have not love,  it profits me nothing.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]Love  suffers long, and is kind; love  envies not; love  vaunts not itself, is not puffed up,
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]Does not behave itself unseemly, seeks not her own, is not easily provoked, thinks no evil;
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]Rejoices not in iniquity, but rejoices in the truth;
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]Bears all things, believes all things, hopes all things, endures all things.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]Love  never fails: but whether there be prophecies, they shall fail; whether there be tongues, they shall cease; whether there be knowledge, it shall vanish away.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]For we know in part, and we prophesy in part.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]But when that which is perfect has come, then that which is in part shall be done away.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]When I was a child, I spoke as a child, I understood as a child, I thought as a child: but when I became a man, I put away childish things.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]For now we see through a glass, darkly; but then face to face: now I know in part; but then shall I know even as also I am known.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]And now abides faith, hope, love,  these three; but the greatest of these is love.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 14"
.\"
.PP
.DROPCAP "F" 2 COND 90
ollow after love,  and desire spiritual gifts, but rather that all of you may prophesy.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]For he that speaks in an unknown tongue speaks not unto men, but unto God: for no man understands him; nevertheless in the spirit  he speaks mysteries.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]But he that prophesies speaks unto men to edification, and exhortation, and comfort.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]He that speaks in an unknown tongue edifies himself; but he that prophesies edifies the church.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]I would that all of you all spoke with tongues but rather that all of you prophesied: for greater is he that prophesies than he that speaks with tongues, except he interpret, that the church may receive edifying.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]Now, brethren, if I come unto you speaking with tongues, what shall I profit you, except I shall speak to you either by revelation, or by knowledge, or by prophesying, or by doctrine?
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]And even things without life giving sound, whether pipe or harp, except they give a distinction in the sounds, how shall it be known what is piped or harped?
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]For if the trumpet give an uncertain sound, who shall prepare himself to the battle?
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]So likewise all of you, except all of you utter by the tongue words  easy to be understood, how shall it be known what is spoken? for all of you shall speak into the air.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]There are, it may be, so many kinds of voices in the world, and none of them is without signification.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]Therefore if I know not the meaning of the voice, I shall be unto him that speaks a barbarian, and he that speaks shall be a barbarian unto me.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]Even so all of you, forasmuch as all of you are zealous of spiritual  gifts, seek that all of you may excel to the edifying of the church.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Wherefore let him that speaks in an unknown tongue pray that he may interpret.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]For if I pray in an unknown tongue, my spirit  prays, but my understanding is unfruitful.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]What is it then? I will pray with the spirit,  and I will pray with the understanding also: I will sing with the spirit,  and I will sing with the understanding also.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]Else when you shall bless with the spirit,  how shall he that occupies the room of the unlearned say Amen at your giving of thanks, seeing he understands not what you says?
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]For you verily give thanks well, but the other is not edified.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]I thank my God, I speak with tongues more than all of you all:
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]Yet in the church I had rather speak five words  with my understanding, that by my voice I might teach others also, than ten thousand words  in an unknown tongue.
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]Brethren, be not children in understanding: nevertheless in malice be all of you children, but in understanding be men.
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]In the law it is written, With men of other tongues and other lips will I speak unto this people; and yet for all that will they not hear me, says the LORD.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]Wherefore tongues are for a sign, not to them that believe, but to them that believe not: but prophesying serves not for them that believe not, but for them which believe.
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]If therefore the whole church be come together into one place, and all speak with tongues, and there come in those that are unlearned, or unbelievers, will they not say that all of you are mad?
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]But if all prophesy, and there come in one that believes not, or one unlearned, he is convinced of all, he is judged of all:
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]And thus are the secrets of his heart made manifest; and so falling down on his face he will worship God, and report that God is in you truthfully.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]How is it then, brethren? when all of you come together, every one of you has a psalm, has a doctrine, has a tongue, has a revelation, has an interpretation. Let all things be done unto edifying.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]If any man speak in an unknown tongue, let it be by two, or at the most by three, and that by course; and let one interpret.
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]But if there be no interpreter, let him keep silence in the church; and let him speak to himself, and to God.
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]Let the prophets speak two or three, and let the other judge.
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]If any thing be revealed to another that sits by, let the first hold his peace.
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]For all of you may all prophesy one by one, that all may learn, and all may be comforted.
\*[SUP]32\*[SUPX]And the spirits  of the prophets are subject to the prophets.
\*[SUP]33\*[SUPX]For God is not the author of confusion, but of peace, as in all churches of the saints.
\*[SUP]34\*[SUPX]Let your women keep silence in the churches: for it is not permitted unto them to speak; but they are commanded to be under obedience as also says the law.
\*[SUP]35\*[SUPX]And if they will learn any thing, let them ask their husbands at home: for it is a shame for women to speak in the church.
\*[SUP]36\*[SUPX]What? came the word  of God out from you? or came it unto you only?
\*[SUP]37\*[SUPX]If any man think himself to be a prophet, or spiritual, let him acknowledge that the things that I write unto you are the commandments of the Lord.
\*[SUP]38\*[SUPX]But if any man be ignorant, let him be ignorant.
\*[SUP]39\*[SUPX]Wherefore, brethren, covet to prophesy, and forbid not to speak with tongues.
\*[SUP]40\*[SUPX]Let all things be done decently and in order.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 15"
.\"
.PP
