aul, a servant of God, and an apostle of Jesus Christ, according to the faith of God's elect, and the acknowledging of the truth which is after godliness;
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]In hope of eternal life, which God, that cannot lie, promised before the world began;
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]But has in due times manifested his word  through preaching, which is committed unto me according to the commandment of God our Saviour;
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]To Titus, mine own son after the common faith: Grace, mercy, and peace, from God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ our Saviour.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]For this cause left I you in Crete, that you should set in order the things that are lacking, and ordain elders in every city, as I had appointed you:
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]If any be blameless, the husband of one wife, having faithful children not accused of riot or unruly.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]For a bishop must be blameless, as the steward of God; not self-willed, not soon angry, not given to wine, not an attacker, not given to filthy illegal gain;
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]But a lover of hospitality, a lover of good men, sober, just, holy, temperate;
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]Holding fast the faithful word  as he has been taught, that he may be able by sound doctrine both to exhort and to convince the gainsayers.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]For there are many unruly and vain talkers and deceivers, specially they of the circumcision:
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]Whose mouths must be stopped, who subvert whole houses, teaching things which they ought not, for filthy illegal gain's sake.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]One of themselves, even a prophet of their own, said, The Cretians are always liars, evil beasts, sluggards.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]This witness is true. Wherefore rebuke them sharply, that they may be sound in the faith;
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]Not giving heed to Jewish fables, and commandments of men, that turn from the truth.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]Unto the pure all things are pure: but unto them that are defiled and unbelieving is nothing pure; but even their mind and conscience is defiled.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]They profess that they know God; but in works they deny him, being abominable, and disobedient, and unto every good work reprobate.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 2"
.\"
.PP
.DROPCAP "B" 2 COND 90
ut speak you the things which become sound doctrine:
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]That the aged men be sober, grave, temperate, sound in faith, in love,  in patience.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]The aged women likewise, that they be in behaviour as becomes holiness, not false accusers, not given to much wine, teachers of good things;
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]That they may teach the young women to be sober, to love their husbands, to love their children,
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]To be discreet, chaste, keepers at home, good, obedient to their own husbands, that the word  of God be not blasphemed.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]Young men likewise exhort to be sober minded.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]In all things showing yourself a pattern of good works: in doctrine showing incorruptness, gravity, sincerity,
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]Sound speech,  that cannot be condemned; that he that is of the contrary part may be ashamed, having no evil thing to say of you.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]Exhort servants to be obedient unto their own masters, and to please them well in all things; not answering again;
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]Not embezzling, but showing all good fidelity; that they may adorn the doctrine of God our Saviour in all things.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]For the grace of God that brings salvation has appeared to all men,
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]Teaching us that, denying ungodliness and worldly lusts, we should live soberly, righteously, and godly, in this present world;
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Looking for that blessed hope, and the glorious appearing of the great God and our Saviour Jesus Christ;
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]Who gave himself for us, that he might redeem us from all iniquity, and purify unto himself an exclusive people, zealous of good works.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]These things speak, and exhort, and rebuke with all authority. Let no man despise you.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 3"
.\"
.PP
.DROPCAP "P" 2 COND 90
ut them in mind to be subject to principalities and powers, to obey magistrates, to be ready to every good work,
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]To speak evil of no man, to be no brawlers, but gentle, showing all meekness unto all men.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]For we ourselves also were sometimes foolish, disobedient, deceived, serving divers lusts and pleasures, living in malice and envy, hateful, and hating one another.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]But after that the kindness and love of God our Saviour toward man appeared,
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]Not by works of righteousness which we have done, but according to his mercy he saved us, by the washing of regeneration, and renewing of the Holy Spirit;
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]Which he shed on us abundantly through Jesus Christ our Saviour;
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]That being justified by his grace, we should be made heirs according to the hope of eternal life.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]This is a faithful saying,  and these things I will that you affirm constantly, that they which have believed in God might be careful to maintain good works. These things are good and profitable unto men.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]But avoid foolish questions, and genealogies, and contentions, and strivings about the law; for they are useless and vain.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]A man that is an heretic after the first and second admonition reject;
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]Knowing that he that is such is subverted, and sins, being condemned of himself.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]When I shall send Artemas unto you, or Tychicus, be diligent to come unto me to Nicopolis: for I have determined there to winter.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Bring Zenas the lawyer and Apollos on their journey diligently, that nothing be lacking unto them.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]And let our's also learn to maintain good works for necessary uses, that they be not unfruitful.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]All that are with me salute you. Greet them that love us in the faith. Grace be with you all. Amen.
