ames, a servant of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ, to the twelve tribes which are scattered abroad, greeting.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]My brethren, count it all joy when all of you fall into divers temptations;
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]Knowing this, that the trying of your faith works patience.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]But let patience have her perfect work, that all of you may be perfect and entire, lacking nothing.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]If any of you lack wisdom, let him ask of God, that gives to all men liberally, and reproaches not; and it shall be given him.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]But let him ask in faith, nothing wavering. For he that wavers is like a wave of the sea driven with the wind and tossed.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]For let not that man think that he shall receive any thing of the Lord.
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]A double minded man is unstable in all his ways.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]Let the brother of low degree rejoice in that he is exalted:
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]But the rich, in that he is made low: because as the flower of the grass he shall pass away.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]For the sun is no sooner risen with a burning heat, but it withers the grass, and the flower thereof falls, and the grace of the fashion of it perishes: so also shall the rich man fade away in his ways.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]Blessed is the man that endures temptation: for when he is tried, he shall receive the crown of life, which the Lord has promised to them that love him.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Let no man say when he is tempted, I am tempted of God: for God cannot be tempted with evil, neither tempts he any man:
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]But every man is tempted, when he is drawn away of his own lust, and enticed.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]Then when lust has conceived, it brings forth sin: and sin, when it is finished, brings forth death.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]Do not go astray, my beloved brethren.
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]Every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, and comes down from the Father of lights, with whom is no variableness, neither shadow of turning.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]Of his own will brings forth he us with the word  of truth, that we should be a kind of first- fruits of his creatures.
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]Wherefore, my beloved brethren, let every man be swift to hear, slow to speak, slow to wrath:
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]For the wrath of man works not the righteousness of God.
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]Wherefore lay apart all filthiness and abundance of evil, and receive with meekness the implanted word,  which is able to save your souls.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]But be all of you doers of the word,  and not hearers only, deceiving your own selves.
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]For if any be a hearer of the word,  and not a doer, he is like unto a man beholding his natural face in a glass:
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]For he beholds himself, and goes his way, and immediately forgets what manner of man he was.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]But whoso looks into the perfect law of liberty, and continues therein, he being not a forgetful hearer, but a doer of the work, this man shall be blessed in his deed.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]If any man among you seem to be religious, and bridles not his tongue, but deceives his own heart, this man's religion is vain.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]Pure religion and undefiled before God and the Father is this, To visit the fatherless and widows in their affliction, and to keep himself unspotted from the world.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 2"
.\"
.PP
.DROPCAP "M" 2 COND 90
y brethren, have not the faith of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Lord of glory, with respect of persons.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]For if there come unto your assembly a man with a gold ring, in goodly apparel, and there come in also a poor man in vile raiment;
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]And all of you have respect to him that wears the cheerful clothing, and say unto him, Sit you here in a good place; and say to the poor, Stand you there, or sit here under my footstool:
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]Are all of you not then partial in yourselves, and are become judges of evil thoughts?
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]Hearken, my beloved brethren, Has not God chosen the poor of this world rich in faith, and heirs of the kingdom which he has promised to them that love him?
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]But all of you have despised the poor. Do not rich men oppress you, and draw you before the judgment seats?
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]Do not they blaspheme that worthy name by the which all of you are called?
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]If all of you fulfill the royal law according to the scripture, You shall love your neighbour as yourself, all of you do well:
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]But if all of you have respect to persons, all of you commit sin, and are convinced of the law as transgressors.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]For whosoever shall keep the whole law, and yet offend in one point, he is guilty of all.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]For he that said, Do not commit adultery, said also, Do not kill. Now if you commit no adultery, yet if you kill, you are become a transgressor of the law.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]So speak all of you, and so do, as they that shall be judged by the law of liberty.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]For he shall have judgment without mercy, that has showed no mercy; and mercy rejoices against judgment.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]What does it profit, my brethren, though a man say he has faith, and have not works? can faith save him?
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]If a brother or sister be naked, and destitute of daily food,
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]And one of you say unto them, Depart in peace, be all of you warmed and filled; notwithstanding all of you give them not those things which are necessary to the body; what does it profit?
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]Even so faith, if it has not works, is dead, being alone.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]Yea, a man may say, You have faith, and I have works: show me your faith without your works, and I will show you my faith by my works.
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]You believe that there is one God; you do well: the devils also believe, and tremble.
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]But will you know, O vain man, that faith without works is dead?
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]Was not Abraham our father justified by works, when he had offered Isaac his son upon the altar?
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]See you how faith wrought with his works, and by works was faith made perfect?
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]And the scripture was fulfilled which says, Abraham believed God, and it was imputed unto him for righteousness: and he was called the Friend of God.
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]All of you see then how that by works a man is justified, and not by faith only.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]Likewise also was not Rahab the harlot justified by works, when she had received the messengers, and had sent them out another way?
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]For as the body without the spirit  is dead, so faith without works is dead also.
.HEADING 2 "Chapter 3"
.\"
.PP
.DROPCAP "M" 2 COND 90
y brethren, be not many masters, knowing that we shall receive the greater condemnation.
\*[SUP]2\*[SUPX]For in many things we offend all. If any man offend not in word,  the same is a perfect man, and able also to bridle the whole body.
\*[SUP]3\*[SUPX]Behold, we put bits in the horses' mouths, that they may obey us; and we turn about their whole body.
\*[SUP]4\*[SUPX]Behold also the ships, which though they be so great, and are driven of fierce winds, yet are they turned about with a very small helm, anywhere the governor decides.
\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]Even so the tongue is a little member, and boasts great things. Behold, how great a matter a little fire kindles!
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]And the tongue is a fire, a world of iniquity: so is the tongue among our members, that it defiles the whole body, and sets on fire the course of nature; and it is set on fire of hell.
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]For every kind of beasts, and of birds, and of serpents, and of things in the sea, is tamed, and has been tamed of mankind:
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]But the tongue can no man tame; it is an unruly evil, full of deadly poison.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]Therewith bless we God, even the Father; and therewith curse we men, which are made after the embodiment of God.
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]Out of the same mouth proceeds blessing and cursing. My brethren, these things ought not so to be.
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]Does a fountain send forth at the same place sweet water and bitter?
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]Can the fig tree, my brethren, bear olive berries? either a vine, figs? so can no fountain both yield salt water and fresh.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Who is a wise man and imbued with knowledge among you? let him show out of a good conversation his works with meekness of wisdom.
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]But if all of you have bitter envying and strife in your hearts, glory not, and lie not against the truth.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]This wisdom descends not from above, but is earthly, sensual, devilish.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]For where envying and strife is, there is confusion and every evil work.
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]But the wisdom that is from above is first pure, then peaceable, gentle, and easy to be implored, full of mercy and good fruits, without partiality, and without hypocrisy.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]And the fruit of righteousness is sown in peace of them that make peace.
